asing in size from small at the top to medium in the middle and large at the bottom. The largest biscuit dominates the foreground before the animation focuses on a single biscuit.\n\nA stylized diagram of a dog’s mouth appears: pink gums with rows of rounded yellow-orange teeth above and below. A Milk-Bone biscuit is positioned horizontally between the teeth. The teeth close down on it, and the biscuit breaks into chunks. As the chewing action repeats, the biscuit pieces scrape between the teeth. The yellow-orange coloring on the teeth gradually gives way to bright white sections, suggesting stains being cleaned away. Several cycles show the mouth opening with biscuit pieces between the teeth, then closing as the pieces crumble further. By the end of the animation, the teeth are shown mostly clean and white, with the mouth closed in a neat, simplified diagram.\n\nThe scene returns to the grassy outdoor setting. Three real dogs stand behind the three Milk-Bone boxes arranged in a row. On the left is a small white fluffy dog behind the small-dog box, in the center a medium brown-and-white beagle-like dog behind the medium-dog box, and on the right the large tan-and-white collie behind the large-dog box. The dogs lower their heads toward the boxes and the grass, sniffing and eating. The collie bends down near the right box and appears to take or chew a biscuit. The beagle moves forward between the boxes, nose down in the grass, while the small white dog peers over and around the left box.\n\nIn the final product display, the three Milk-Bone boxes remain lined up in the grass with the dogs partially visible behind them. Large white text appears across the bottom reading “Better Teeth Cleaner.” The collie at the right continues to hold or chew a biscuit near the large-dog box, while the beagle and small white dog remain close to their matching boxes.",
